#: src/users/frequent-problems.md:3
msgid "Why does my submitted job appear to stuck in the queue forever?"
msgstr ""

#: src/users/frequent-problems.md:5
msgid ""
"One way to diagnose the problem is to click on the `Scheduler ID` and look "
"at the scheduler's description. If the `Reason` variable equals to:"
msgstr ""

#: src/users/frequent-problems.md:8
msgid ""
"`QOSMaxWallDurationPerJobLimit`: Your job requested wall time for too long "
"and will stick in the queue forever. Please cancel the current job, copy the "
"job, and adjust the wall time to be under your role's "
"[limitations](./limitations.html)."
msgstr ""

#: src/users/frequent-problems.md:13
msgid "Why my job cannot use existing GPU?"
msgstr ""

#: src/users/frequent-problems.md:15
msgid ""
"Especially for students groups, only MIG GPUs are allowed. By default, your "
"script is not usually specified to use MIG GPUs for computation, but full "
"GPUs. As the job is only allocated for MIG GPUs, requesting a full GPU "
"inside might be problematic. To make your job use MIG GPUs, some "
"environmental declarations are needed. In this case, we specify \"CUDA "
"devices\" to be a MIG GPU via declaring `CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES` environment "
"variable as a MIG GPU ID. You can copy this line of the script before the "
"execution line of the program."
msgstr ""

#: src/users/frequent-problems.md:24
msgid ""
"$(\n"
"    nvidia-smi -L | \\\n"
"        grep -Eo 'MIG-[0-9a-f]{8}(-[0-9a-f]{4}){3}-[0-9a-f]{12}' | \\\n"
"        head -n 1\n"
")\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/users/frequent-problems.md:31
msgid ""
"The script basically lists all available GPUs with UUID. Then, we grab the "
"first MIG GPU ID (the one Slurm allocates for us), and declaring it the CUDA "
"device to be used."
msgstr ""

